Yes — we can make `/auth/start` duplicate-safe **without breaking multiple users or multiple browsers**.

The trick is:

👉 lock only **per browser session**, not globally.

So:

* User A browser works normally ✅
* User B browser works normally ✅
* 100 users same time works ✅
* only duplicate rapid clicks from the **same browser session** are ignored/reused ✅

---

# Best Solution: Session-scoped auth pending guard

Use the existing `HttpSession`.

Each browser gets its own session cookie.

So duplicates are isolated naturally.

---

# How it works

When `/auth/start` is called:

## First request from browser

```text id="th3a9o"
No pending auth
→ create transaction
→ mark AUTH_PENDING
→ redirect to Keycloak
```

## Second duplicate request 300ms later (same browser)

```text id="40lv7n"
AUTH_PENDING exists
→ reuse existing redirect OR ignore
```

## Another user in another browser

Different session:

```text id="f3pj76"
No pending auth
→ proceeds normally
```

---

# Will it break multiple users?

## NO

Because session storage is separate per browser cookie.

User A:

```text id="e5x2mu"
session=ABC123
```

User B:

```text id="nyfvg0"
session=XYZ999
```

Each gets own lock.

---

# Implementation (Recommended)

## In `startAuthentication(...)`

```java
@GetMapping("/start")
public ResponseEntity<Void> startAuthentication(
        @RequestHeader(value = "APP_ID", required = false) String headerAppId,
        @RequestParam(value = "appId", required = false) String queryAppId,
        HttpServletRequest request
) {

    String appId = headerAppId != null && !headerAppId.isBlank()
            ? headerAppId
            : queryAppId;

    HttpSession session = request.getSession(true);

    String pendingRedirect =
            (String) session.getAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_REDIRECT");

    Long pendingTime =
            (Long) session.getAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_TIME");

    // if duplicate within 10 sec, reuse existing redirect
    if (pendingRedirect != null && pendingTime != null) {

        long age = System.currentTimeMillis() - pendingTime;

        if (age < 10000) {
            log.info("Duplicate auth/start detected, reusing redirect");
            HttpHeaders headers = new HttpHeaders();
            headers.setLocation(URI.create(pendingRedirect));
            return new ResponseEntity<>(headers, HttpStatus.FOUND);
        }
    }

    String redirectUrl = authService.startAuthentication(appId);

    session.setAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_REDIRECT", redirectUrl);
    session.setAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_TIME", System.currentTimeMillis());

    HttpHeaders headers = new HttpHeaders();
    headers.setLocation(URI.create(redirectUrl));
    return new ResponseEntity<>(headers, HttpStatus.FOUND);
}
```

---

# Clear it after callback

In `/callback`

```java
HttpSession session = request.getSession(false);

if (session != null) {
    session.removeAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_REDIRECT");
    session.removeAttribute("AUTH_PENDING_TIME");
}
```

This resets for future logins.

---

# Why this is safe

## Same browser accidental double hit

Second request reuses same redirect.

## Different browser / user

Different session, unaffected.

## Real login again later

After callback, lock cleared.

---

# Better than global Redis lock

Do **NOT** lock by appId globally.

Bad:

```text id="gn7n9g"
B2BOOST_BE locked
```

That would break many users.

---

# If no session yet?

Calling:

```java
request.getSession(true)
```

creates one.

Perfectly fine for auth start.

---

# Even stronger version (recommended)

Instead of storing redirect URL only, store generated `state`.

Then if duplicate comes, reuse exact pending state transaction.

---

# What if user opens two tabs intentionally?

Same browser session usually same cookie.

Then second tab within 10 sec reuses same auth request.

This is usually acceptable.

If you want separate tabs independent, we can use a **tab token** later.

---

# My recommendation for your case

Use:

## 10-second duplicate window

Enough to catch browser double requests.

---

# Logs to add

```java
log.info("Session={} pending auth age={}ms", session.getId(), age);
```

You’ll see duplicate suppression clearly.

